message.content: A Quercus lobata is a species of oak tree native to California, Oregon, and Nevada. It is a deciduous tree that can grow up to 100 feet tall, with a broad and spreading canopy. The bark of the Quercus lobata is light gray and deeply furrowed. The leaves are large, lobed, and have a pale green color, turning orange and brown in the fall. The acorns of the Quercus lobata are large and have a distinctive cap that covers a third of the nut. It is a popular tree in landscaping and is also used for lumber and firewood. The Quercus lobata can be found in a variety of habitats, from valleys to hillsides and slopes.
